==English==

===Etymology===
Dutch ''ranten'' 'talk nonsense, rave'.

===Pronunciation===

{{US}} ([[SAMPA]]): [r{nt]

===Noun===
[[Category:English nouns]]
'''rant'''

# A criticism done by ranting.
# A wild, incoherent, emotional articulation.
# An exposition writen,or more often verbal,where emotionality supercedes rationality. It's purpose is a call to action, often identifying a target for ire and a path to resolution. Due to the perjoritive connotation of the term it is a descriptor that is often subjective, most often applied to messages disagreed with. IE: Hitler's speeches were rants, Churchill's were spellbinding.

===Verb===
[[Category:English verbs]]
{{en-infl-reg-consonant|rant||}}

# To speak or shout at length in an uncontrollable anger.
# To criticize by ranting.

